d power in early modern Italy. By revealing the literary motifs in men's and women's writing about gender she maps how certain figures in Petrarch's writing transmitted gendered ideas of power and reflected a growing anxiety about women as public figures. This work includes nuanced analyses of poetry, linguistic treatises, debates on imitation, representations of gender and epistolary correspondence in Latin and Italian. Writing Beloveds is a landmark study that highlights the new social reality of women writers in early modern Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHumanism in literature. 0aItalian poetryxHistory and criticismy16th century. 0aItalian poetryy16th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPetrarchism. 0aPolitics in literature. 0aSex role in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Italian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066594940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781487514716zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487514716zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487514716/original  a978-3-11-066594-9 University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127365-5 ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA